The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, April 06, 2004 				 Power-packed NTPC strategy 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 				 	 NTPC chief C. P. Jain in New Delhi on Monday. (PTI)																								New Delhi, April 5: National Thermal Power Corporation today announced major investments in hydroelectric power sector during the next five years to generate 10,000 megawatt of power at a cost of more than Rs 15,000-20,000 crore. 																								The company reported a 36 per cent jump in net profit in 2003-04 at Rs 4,905 crore. NTPC also plans to launch its IPO in the current financial year, probably as early as August. 																								NTPCs gross revenues rose to Rs 25,184 crore in 2003-04 as against Rs 19,850 crore in 2002-03. 																								The power generating public sector companys initiatives in hydroelectric power includes 10 projects worth 5361 MW, which form part of the Prime Ministers 50,000 MW hydro initiative. About 8,000 MW of projects are at different stages of implementation. 																								C. P. Jain, chairman and managing director, NTPC, said: As part of the Tenth Five Year Plan target of adding 9370 MW, we have already commissioned more than 1500 MW. We have set a target of adding projects with a capacity of more than 6210 MW. Most of these are already under various stages of implementation and bids have been invited for 1160 MW. The company has set a target to become a 56,000-MW company by 2017. NTPC will earmark 0.5 per cent of its net profit for research and development every year. 																								With an authorised share capital of Rs 10,000 crore and paid-up capital base of Rs 7812.5 crore, we plan to tap the market this fiscal to widen our equity base. The board has approved the plan and we will file the prospectus with the Sebi for necessary clearances. We have also received the governments approval. The proposal is to float 5 per cent of our equity, said Jain. 																								He said NTPC plans to appoint merchant bankers and lead managers for the issue by the end of this month. The draft prospectus would be filed with the Sebi by the end of May and the pricing would be finalised once the advisors are appointed. 																								NTPC plans to raise over Rs 3,000 crore through bonds and borrowings. The corporation has set a budgetary target of Rs 4,755 crore for 2004-05, which is revised from Rs 4,515 crore target set last year. The company plans to raise it through internal accruals, borrowings and bonds. 																								Meanwhile, stung by adverse impact of the new tariff order, NTPC will file a review petition before the Central Electricity Regulatory Commission (CERC). 
